Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shader_reference/shader_functions.rst
Summary: A list of built-in geometric functions for vector and matrix manipulation available in the Godot shader language.

Geometric functions

* length(vec_type x) -> float: Vector length.
* distance(vec_type a, vec_type b) -> float: Distance between vectors, i.e. `length(a - b)`.
* dot(vec_type a, vec_type b) -> float: Dot product.
* cross(vec3 a, vec3 b) -> vec3: Cross product.
* normalize(vec_type x) -> vec_type: Normalize to unit length.
* reflect(vec3 I, vec3 N) -> vec3: Reflect.
* refract(vec3 I, vec3 N, float eta) -> vec3: Refract.
* faceforward(vec_type N, vec_type I, vec_type Nref) -> vec_type: If `dot(Nref, I)` < 0, return `N`, otherwise `-N`.
* matrixCompMult(mat_type x, mat_type y) -> mat_type: Matrix component multiplication.
* outerProduct(vec_type column, vec_type row) -> mat_type: Matrix outer product.
* transpose(mat_type m) -> mat_type: Transpose matrix.
* determinant(mat_type m) -> float: Matrix determinant.
* inverse(mat_type m) -> mat_type: Inverse matrix.
---CHUNK---
Document: shader_functions
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shader_reference/shader_functions.rst
Summary: This chunk describes built-in geometric and matrix functions available in Godot shaders, such as length, distance, dot, cross, normalize, reflect, refract, and various matrix operations.

Method: float length(vec_type x)
Returns the length of the vector, i.e. `sqrt(x[0] * x[0] + x[1] * x[1] + ... + x[n] * x[n])`. The parameter `x` is the vector.

Method: float distance(vec_type a, vec_type b)
Returns the distance between the two points `a` and `b`. This is equivalent to `length(b - a)`.

Method: float dot(vec_type a, vec_type b)
Returns the dot product of two vectors, `a` and `b`. This is equivalent to `a.x * b.x + a.y * b.y + ...`.

Method: vec3 cross(vec3 a, vec3 b)
Returns the cross product of two vectors, `a` and `b`.
GLSL:
    vec2( a.y * b.z - b.y * a.z,
          a.z * b.x - b.z * a.x,
          a.x * b.z - b.x * a.y)

Method: vec_type normalize(vec_type x)
Returns a vector with the same direction as `x` but with a length of `1.0`.

Method: vec3 reflect(vec3 I, vec3 N)
Calculates the reflection direction for an incident vector `I` and a surface normal `N`. The reflection direction is calculated as `I - 2.0 * dot(N, I) * N`. Note: `N` should be normalized in order to achieve the desired result.

Method: vec3 refract(vec3 I, vec3 N, float eta)
Calculates the refraction direction for an incident vector. For a given incident vector `I`, surface normal `N`, and ratio of indices of refraction `eta`, this function returns the refraction vector, `R`. `R` is calculated as:
GLSL:
    k = 1.0 - eta * eta * (1.0 - dot(N, I) * dot(N, I));
    if (k < 0.0)
        R = genType(0.0);       // or genDType(0.0)
    else
        R = eta * I - (eta * dot(N, I) + sqrt(k)) * N;
Note: The input parameters `I` and `N` should be normalized in order to achieve the desired result.

Method: vec_type faceforward(vec_type N, vec_type I, vec_type Nref)
Returns a vector pointing in the same direction as another. It orients a vector `N` to point away from a surface as defined by its normal. If `dot(Nref, I) < 0`, `faceforward` returns `N`; otherwise, it returns `-N`.

Method: mat_type matrixCompMult(mat_type x, mat_type y)
Performs a component-wise multiplication of two matrices, `x` and `y`. This yields a result matrix where each component, `result[i][j]`, is computed as the scalar product of `x[i][j]` and `y[i][j]`.

Method: mat_type outerProduct(vec_type column, vec_type row)
Calculates the outer product of a pair of vectors. It performs a linear algebraic matrix multiplication of `column * row`, yielding a matrix whose number of rows is the number of components in `column` and whose number of columns is the number of components in `row`.

Method: mat_type transpose(mat_type m)
Calculates the transpose of a matrix `m`. It returns a new matrix that is the transpose of the input.

Method: float determinant(mat_type m)
Calculates the determinant of a matrix `m`.

Method: mat_type inverse(mat_type m)
Calculates the inverse of a matrix `m`. The values in the returned matrix are undefined if `m` is singular or poorly-conditioned (nearly singular).
---CHUNK---
Document: shader_reference/shader_functions
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shader_reference/shader_functions.rst
Summary: This chunk describes built-in shader functions for component-wise vector comparisons and boolean vector operations.

Comparison functions

*   lessThan(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '<' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   greaterThan(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '>' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   lessThanEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '<=' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   greaterThanEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '>=' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   equal(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '==' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   notEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y) -> vec_bool_type: Performs a component-wise boolean comparison using the '!=' operator on int, uint, or float vectors.
*   any(vec_bool_type x) -> bool: Returns `true` if any component of the boolean vector `x` is `true`, and `false` otherwise.
*   all(vec_bool_type x) -> bool: Returns `true` if all components of the boolean vector `x` are `true`, and `false` otherwise.
*   not(vec_bool_type x) -> vec_bool_type: Inverts the boolean vector, returning a new boolean vector where each component is the logical opposite of the corresponding component in `x`.
---CHUNK---
Document: shader_functions
Path: godot/tutorials/shaders/shader_reference/shader_functions.rst
Summary: This chunk describes built-in shader functions for component-wise vector comparison and boolean vector operations.

Method: vec_bool_type lessThan(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise less-than comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] < y[i]`.

Method: vec_bool_type greaterThan(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise greater-than comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] > y[i]`.

Method: vec_bool_type lessThanEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise less-than-or-equal comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] <= y[i]`.

Method: vec_bool_type greaterThanEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise greater-than-or-equal comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] >= y[i]`.

Method: vec_bool_type equal(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise equal-to comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] == y[i]`.

Method: vec_bool_type notEqual(vec_type x, vec_type y)
Performs a component-wise not-equal-to comparison of two vectors, `x` and `y`. Returns a boolean vector in which each element `i` is computed as `x[i] != y[i]`.

Method: bool any(vec_bool_type x)
Returns `true` if any element of a boolean vector `x` is `true`, and `false` otherwise. Functionally equivalent to:
    bool any(bvec x) {     // bvec can be bvec2, bvec3 or bvec4
        bool result = false;
        int i;
        for (i = 0; i < x.length(); ++i) {
            result |= x[i];
        }
        return result;
    }

Method: bool all(vec_bool_type x)
Returns `true` if all elements of a boolean vector `x` are `true`, and `false` otherwise. Functionally equivalent to:
    bool all(bvec x)       // bvec can be bvec2, bvec3 or bvec4
    {
        bool result = true;
        int i;
        for (i = 0; i < x.length(); ++i)
        {
            result &= x[i];
        }
        return result;
    }

Method: vec_bool_type not(vec_bool_type x)
Logically inverts a boolean vector `x`. Returns a new boolean vector for which each element `i` is computed as `!x[i]`.
---CHUNK---
